strategy_text: With the grasping tool, I found I was not grabbing the block squarely for the first few times.  By turning my wrist a bit more to come at the block straight on, I felt i was more successful in grabbing the object.

hypothesis_guess_1: I would imagine at least two different expectations. One, that the perception of one’s arm in VR mimics the actual location of it; and two, that the performance would be improved with repetition.
hypothesis_guess_2: My guess is that, even with incredibly accurate tracking of body location, there may still be differences in VR eye-body coordination vs physical world.  I would think that the accuracy and pace whereby one completes tasks will be a measure of this difference.
challenge: Without question, the grabber tool.  Having to manage depth perception with a tool rather than my hand itself was much more challenging.   I also felt that my perception of where my wrist, elbow, and forearm were without the visual cue were pretty variable
hypothesis_guess_1_post: Now I’m thinking that the study was more focused toward prosthetic use and that the researchers were expecting that within the VR environment the distinction between tool and physical body part would become blurred.
hypothesis_guess_2_post: Within very high fidelity VR environments, tools in the physical environment could potentially feel as if they are part of the subject’s body

strategy_text:
I made visual notes of where parts of my arm were and click the circular pad when they fell into the area. 
For the part of the study when I was tasked with picking up the block with the clamp, I attempted to clamp different parts of the block to pick it up more efficiently. I found that clamping in the high center of the block allowed me to swiftly and more accurately raise and place the block in its respective squares.
strategy_modify: I replicated strategies when performing the same tasks again.
hypothesis_guess_1: I think the researchers may have predicted that the equipment would help virtual reality calibrate/accurately represent the range of motion of the right arm.
hypothesis_guess_2: The point of the study might be to develop programming that accurately depicts the range of motion of an appendage, in this case the focus was on the right arm.
challenge: I found the clamp part of the experiment most challenging because a quarter way into the challenge, the inside of my palm grew sore from gripping the clamp on and off again.
hypothesis_guess_1_post: I think the researchers may have expected to see the participant start to associate physical sense with the actions of the virtual arm.
hypothesis_guess_2_post: I now think that the researchers were testing for a mental change in distinction of the participants own bodily senses.
